### 17. NURSE NOTES

**Description:** Short, medically relevant note capturing what the NURSE elicited from the patient during triage/history-taking and any direct observations the nurse made. This is the contextual information around the complaint that doesn''t fit into any earlier segment.

**What to include:**
- âœ… Context/mechanism around the chief complaint (e.g., "pain started after playing football 3 days ago", "fall from bike yesterday evening", "ate outside food before vomiting started")
- âœ… Recent events the nurse elicited (e.g., "took home Paracetamol with partial relief", "consulted local doctor 2 days ago, given antibiotics")
- âœ… Patient appearance / demeanour observations by the nurse (e.g., "patient appears anxious", "in mild distress", "walked in unassisted", "supported by attendant")
- âœ… Any other medically relevant detail the nurse gathered that is NOT already covered in Vitals, Chief Complaints, Past History, or Patient History

**Extraction Rules:**
- âœ… Keep it SHORT â€” 1 to 3 concise sentences. Not a verbatim dump.
- âœ… Medically relevant only. Skip small talk, administrative chatter, and non-clinical observations.
- âœ… If the nurse contributes nothing beyond what is already captured in other segments, return "" (empty string)
- âŒ Do NOT duplicate vitals values, chief complaints, past medical conditions, allergies, or current medications â€” those have dedicated segments
- âŒ Do NOT include doctor''s clinical assessment or examination findings â€” those go in DOCTOR_NOTES
- âŒ Do NOT fabricate. If the nurse is not separately heard from, return ""

**Examples:**

"Pain started 3 days ago after playing football. Took home Paracetamol with no relief. Patient walking with mild limp, appears comfortable at rest."

"Fall from two-wheeler this morning. No LOC, no vomiting. Brought outside CT scan report. Patient anxious, accompanied by spouse."

"Vomiting started after eating outside last night. 4 episodes since morning. Took ORS at home. Patient appears mildly dehydrated." 

